         b'/div>\n\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t<div class="post-551 post type-post status'
         b'-publish format-standard hentry category-event category-project cate'
         b'gory-social-networks" id="post-551">\n\t\t\t<h2>The Internet for Act'
         b'ivists: The Good and The Ugly</h2>\n\n\t\t\t<div class="entry">\n\t'
         b'\t\t\t<p>I just got back from the Internet for Activists conference'
         b'. It was a very stimulating experience: <a href="http://www.bloggerh'
         b'eads.com/">Tim Ireland</a> of Bloggerheads spoke about the importanc'
         b'e of SEO techniques for activists who wish to get their message out '
         b'there. <a href="http://www.ukwatch.net/author/laurie_penny">Laurie P'
         b'enny</a> who writes on Penny Red gave activist bloggers two main rec'
         b'ommendations:</p>\n<ul>\n<li> Engage in comments (openly accept co'
         b'mments and REPLY to them; however, don&#8217;t let stalkers take ove'
         b'r your blog and do so by moderating comments with clear guidelines)<'
         b'/li>\n<li> Go for quality not quantity (write less posts but writ'
         b'e them well)</li>\n</ul>\n<p> who does  her PhD at UCL  recounted '
         b'her experience of using Facebook for rescuing Guy Njike from deporta'
         b'tion. Finally, <a href="http://obamalondon.blogspot.com/">Karin Robi'
         b'nson</a> talked about how she coordinated the activities of the Amer'
         b'icans Abroad for Obama campaign. Interestingly, people earned points'
         b' on the Obama social net website only if they didn&#8217;t sit in fr'
         b'ont of their computers but went out there.</p>\n<p>These examples'
         b' of online activism show that social net websites reduce communicati'
         b'on and coordination costs and, as such,  help people to organize off'
         b'-line activities as well: people who live in the same neighborhood p'
         b'hysically meet for the first time because of  shared interests on th'
         b'e Internet (e.g., activism). Those examples also show that there is '
         b'little merit in <a href="http://mobblog.cs.ucl.ac.uk/2009/02/26/bad-'
         b'science-by-the-head-of-the-royal-institution-susan-greenfield/">Susa'
         b'n Greenfield&#8217;s contemptible  campaign</a>. Frankly I don&#8217'
         b';t blame those who think she should go.</p>\n<p>During these pres'
         b'entations I was thinking about a <strong>student project</strong> id'
         b'ea:</p>\n<ul>\n<li> Design a platform for building campaigns. Idea'
         b'lly, such platforms should be easy to use and should allow people to'
         b' not only engage in online activities but also to easily coordinate '
         b'their off-line activities (e.g., street demonstrations, writing lett'
         b'ers to MPs)</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong> The dark side of activism: Th'
         b'e Ugly Mask</strong></p>\n<p><img alt="" src="http://www.cs.ucl.a'
         b'c.uk/staff/d.quercia/others/mask.jpg" title="mask" class="alignnone"'
         b'/></p>\n<p>The representative of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org'
         b'/wiki/Anonymous_(group)">Anonymous</a> was also invited, and his (?)'
         b' intervention was quite controversial. He concealed his identity wit'
         b'h a mask and spoke on behalf of Anonymous. Here is what Anonymous is'
         b':</p>\n<ul>\n<li>(from The Economist) Now Scientology is under att'
         b'ack from a group of internet activists known only as Anonymous. Orga'
         b'nised from a Wikipedia-style website (editable by anyone) and throug'
         b'h anonymous internet chat rooms, &#8220;Project Chanology&#8221;, as'
         b' the initiative is known, presents no easy target for Scientology&#8'
         b'217;s lawyers. It is promoting cyberwarfare techniques normally asso'
         b'ciated with extortionists, spies and terrorists. Called &#8220;distr'
         b'ibuted denial of service attacks&#8221;, these typically involve usi'
         b'ng networks of infected computers to bombard the target&#8217;s webs'
         b'ites and servers with bogus requests for data, causing them to crash'
         b'. Even governments find this troublesome.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The camp'
         b'aign against Scientology may all be very well. However, the assumpti'
         b'on behind these self-organizing activists is that they are always ri'
         b'ght (they are anonymous and, as such, they are not accountable). Unf'
         b'ortunately, this assumption does not always hold. Indeed, most of th'
         b'e activities the Mask presented were either jokes the audience faile'
         b'd to understand or Internet bullying activities. Worringly, this sel'
         b'f-organizing entity finds it acceptable to launch DoS attacks agains'
         b't websites that happen to disagree with the entity&#8217;s views. Is'
         b' this the right way to go? Can this be even called activism?</p>'
